JOHANNESBURG – Embattled retail giant Steinhoff is planning to reward directors for having to do more work than usual. The embattled company, which is at the centre of an accounting scandal that saw investors lose huge amounts of money, proposed a once-off payments of close to R2-million to three of its senior board members. It said the payments would be for handling the fallout after its accounting fraud scandal late last year. Steinhoff also suggested that all members of its supervisory board should be paid for extra meetings. WATCH: Two cases of insider trading registered in Steinhoff scandal The payments will be voted on at Steinhoff's annual general meeting on 20 April. PriceWaterhouseCoopers is conducting a forensic investigation looking into the firm's books. eNCA